<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0103</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Motoring </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Organisations’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Land Access and Recreation Association (LARA) – Written evidence</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary of Key Issues</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We support the work and consensus recommendations of the Stakeholder Working Group, which underpin this part of the Bill. Our members are not</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">directly</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">affected by the proposals in sections 12-18 of the Bill and the associated Schedules, and we su</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">port the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Stakeholder Working Group’s recommendations (only) as contained within the Bill.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We are very concerned that groups such as the Green Lanes Environmental Action Movement (GLEAM) and the Peak District Green Lanes Association (PDGLA), each with a single-issue objective to restrict or destroy our members’ lawful activities, are making representations such that additional traffic regulation provisions are introduced by the Deregulation Bill, and/or that all unsealed public roads and byways open to all traffic are administratively downgraded to restricted byway status.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">These issues have not been before the Stakeholder Working Group, have not been through any process of public consultation, and are not objectively evidence-based. Far from being deregulatory, these proposals will operate to increase local authority and p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">lice burdens.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">LARA believes that there is no evidential case made for any of these proposals, that they will introduce an additional layer of regulation and burden, and that any change in this area of law and practice should first go through a proper process of public consu</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tation.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Any countryside access </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> (including GLEAM and PDGLA) is able to bring such proposals directly to the Countryside Minister, and to the Rights of Way Review Committee, which is constituted and operated to receive and consider such matters and to make recommendations to the Government.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In our respectful view, what is being proposed to the Committee is not deregulatory, and is simply an attempt to use the Deregulation Bill 2013 to circumvent a proper pr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">cess of public consultation by the appropriate Government Department, and (if nece</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sary) a full and proper process in Parliament.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Our Evidence</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is LARA?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This submission is from LARA, the national forum for the principal groups in cou</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tryside motor sport and recreation. LARA does not </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">organise</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> events, nor act as a governing body, but assists its eighteen member </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, which themselves represent around 600,000 individual members, in a wide range of land access issues.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In March 1986 the Sports Council published its report </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Providing for Motorsport </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Grande'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‑</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">From</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Image to Reality</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> (Professor Martin Elson and team, Oxford Polytechnic). The report concluded that, long overdue, was: “...the formation of a national motorsport ... group which would, through an activist role, and through advocacy and persuasion, become a respected </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">consultee</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> on all aspects of the provision of facilities, and the control of, motorsports...”</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Motorsport took that advice and created the Motoring </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Organisations'</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Land Access and Recreation Association (LARA) in June 1986. Throughout its life LARA and its Members have played an active role in national and local countryside policy debates, with regular attendance at the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Rights of Way Review Committee</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> (Honorary Chairman, Lord Lytton), and one of our specialists has been an active participant in the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Stak</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">holder Working Group</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, whose work is now contained within the Deregulation Bill 2013.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Financial benefits to the rural community</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Motor sport events and recreational visits to the countryside bring considerable f</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">nancial income to the rural economy: start, finish and meal stop venue hire, refres</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ments, bed-and-breakfast and hotel accommodation, etc. In many places the income to hotels and cafes from the motoring community is (they tell us) the difference b</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tween financial viability and closure, particularly because many motorist visitors come out of peak season.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disinformation about our activities</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">On the face of it there is little in the Deregulation Bill 2013 that will directly affect the minor roads which are of crucial importance to the people whom we ultimately represent and advise, but experience has shown us that we must try to point out the possibility of unintended consequences, and counter opportunistic disinfo</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">mation by those opposed to any form of legitimate vehicular access to the countryside other than on main routes. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Take the accusation made to the Committee of ‘a horse fatality’ attributed to trail riders. We know of none, but we do know of many horse events that greatly ben</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">fit </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">from the aid of trail riders, such as those at Chatsworth and Burleigh. We gene</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ally get along very well with horse riders, and LARA has a concordat with the British Horse Society.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We do not shy away from the examples of bad driving which bring many thousands of responsible people into disrepute, and we are working with all others in national and regional committees, and many Local Access Forums (LAF), where we attempt to see all sides of any debate and strongly promote consensus management, not as a theoretical concept but in reality. This is borne out by our recent guidance: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Traffic Management Hierarchy. Good Practice in Traffic Management on Unsealed Public Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. In this we say:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Recreational motoring on unsealed roads and byways is an emotive and complex issue. Some people think that motor vehicles should simply be banned from unsealed roads and nothing is easily going to change that view, but there is increasingly a ‘middle ground’ approach from highway authorities, which seeks to apply a considered ‘least r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">strictive approach’ philosophy to traffic management on our minor highways.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">LARA believes that consensus management of motor traffic on unsealed roads, appr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">priate to the circumstances in each case, together with sufficient maintenance and a r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">alistic expectation of what a byway should be like, is the way ahead.</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Motor sport and recreation form a strong part of Britain’s industrial heritage, providing both ‘classic’ activity, and the modern-era, high-technology industry unde</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pinning circuit racing and rallying.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The situation since 2006</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14pt; padding-left:22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In 2005/6, LARA was closely involved with the passage of the Bill that became the Natural Environment and Rural Communities Act 2006 (NERCA). We were disa</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pointed by the broad-brush approach of NERCA, but it became law and we have adapted to the new statutory environment, and have educated and advised drivers and others accordingly.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Essentially, section 67 of NERCA imposed a backdated cut-off on the statutory pr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">cess, by which ‘new’ byways open to all traffic (BOAT) could be added to the defin</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tive map of public rights of way. The cut-off provision was very effective, catching by its strict-compliance conditions most of the statutory ‘definitive map modification order applications’ already in the system. Since 2006 the only counties where more than a small handful of BOATs have been added to the definitive map are Wiltshire, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Derbyshire and Northumberland, and in the latter two counties, th</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">se BOATs have already been recorded as public roads for as long as county councils have been the highway authority (from 1929) and have been in use by the public with motors du</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ing this period. These are not in any way ‘additional </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">BOATs’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">; r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ther they are long-existing public roads being called and recorded by a different name.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Part of NERCA 2006 was the introduction of a power for National Park Author</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ties to make traffic regulation orders (TRO) on BOATs and unsealed unclassified roads, and (at least) the Yorkshire Dales and Peak District National Park Authorities have done this, while the North York Moors and Lake District have TROs made by the highway authority. Highway authorities are also making TROs in areas of outstanding natural beauty (e.g. Northumberland and Hampshire). LARA has opposed some of these orders (generally not in principle, but because we believe they could be more </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">focussed</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and fairer), and we have no reason to believe that the various traffic a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">thorities with the power to make TROs are not making these where appropriate. Essentially, the power in NERCA is enough, and it works.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We must also mention here the Lake District (and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Cumbria</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hierarchy of Trail Routes</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> scheme, which over approaching twenty years has worked well and shown how an inclusive management </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> gets respect and is effective. The inclusive a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">proach of this scheme is a model that can and should be adapted to other places.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The standard and cost of maintenance and repair</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The standard of ‘good repair’ for BOATs and unsealed roads, and the cost of r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pair, is an issue that has been debated for many years. It is our experience (and that of horse-riders as regards bridleways, and walkers as regards footpaths) that highway authorities often put a price on maintenance and repair far in excess of what it costs in the ‘real world’. Where volunteers get </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">involved,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> or local small contractors, pe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">fectly good jobs are done at a small fraction of authority estimates. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">LARA has recently been researching and setting out just what is the baseline stan</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ard of repair for a ‘cart road’, and it is not a standard that demands £75,000 a mile, or anything like that. As a long-time horse rider, with hands-on experience of repai</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ing byways and bridleways once observed, the three most important elements of maintenance are: ‘drainage, drainage, and drainage’, and that was known to the R</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">mans, long before the era of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">McAdam</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Green roads</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">‘Green roads’ are a national public asset, a multi-user leisure resource that should be protected from further downgrading or closure. Mass downgrading would be akin to the attempted closure of the canal system in the 1960s, and that once-unwanted network has since become a major leisure resource. Green roads, kept open by the passage of traffic, are wildlife corridors, possess high biodiversity, and are ways through surrounding woodland, to which they would revert if unused by motor v</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">hicles. A significant number of green roads that lost public motor vehicular rights due to section 67 of NERCA are now seriously overgrown, choked, and u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">pleasant for, or unusable by, the public on foot, horseback and pedal cycles. The highway author</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ties do not have the resources repeatedly to clear these roads, which were prev</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ously kept usable by the passage of traffic.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Government carried out a very detailed research project on motor vehicles on byways, published in January 2005. This concluded: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">There was no evidence of widespread damage to the byway network from motor vehicles.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">42% of use was land management, 38% of use was recreational, and 20% of use was a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">c</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">cess to property, with recreational use at 38%. If all unsealed roads were downgraded to restricted byways, the land management and access uses would remain with no benefit ot</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">h</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">er than a discriminatory penalty to recreational users.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Motor vehicles can have a beneficial effect, in that they prevent byways becoming ove</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">grown.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Byways are an important resource for people with disabilities ... the ability to drive motor vehicles on byways.</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If all unsealed roads were downgraded to restricted byways, they would still have to be maintained by highway authorities for land management, access, and other u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ers. There is no financial benefit in downgrading, and there is a proven serious </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">disbenefit</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to non-motor traffic in many cases.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Stone roads</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">People often think of byways open to all traffic, and unsealed unclassified roads, as all being ‘green roads’, with no stone or other </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">metalling</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> on the surface. Many are </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">unmetalled</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, and, of those, most are well drained and resilient. Equally, many byways and unclassified roads have a strong stone, or even tarmac, surface, because BOAT status is dependent upon the nature and balance of the use that the road gets, and not what it looks like.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Stone roads have a variety of origins. A few are former turnpike roads, bypassed and never given a ‘blacktop’ in the country road improvement era, which was primarily 1920-1960. Some are the result of the Parliamentary </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">inclosure</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> process, and others are just ... roads, showing what almost all ordinary minor roads were like when m</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tor vehicles started. Unsealed unclassified roads were (with very few e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">x</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ceptions) the ordinary public roads, first recorded in 1929, and then mapped and listed by the highway authorities ever since. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">These were, and are, ordinary public roads, and they were and are the essential network for informal touring (green road driving), </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">organised</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> trials, rallies, and tou</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ing events. This is very well illustrated in the context of ‘classic reliability trials’ for cars and motorcycles.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is a classic reliability trial?</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Classic reliability trials are one of the oldest forms of motor sport with a contin</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ous history going back to before The Great War. In the early days of motoring, manufa</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">turers wished to prove the reliability of their products by undertaking long runs to establish that the vehicle could complete the course within a time schedule. The manufacturers, to prove the virtues of their vehicles on general sale, were keen to stress that these events were on ‘ordinary roads’, and not on ‘freak sections’.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Today’s classic trials reflect the style that was prevalent in the 1930s when works teams from Ford, Austin, Singer, MG and others battled it out for advertising </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ho</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ours</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> over long distances and the steep slopes of country roads. Many of the o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">served sections (the name given to the hills on which the car’s performance is judged) used in the 1930s are still in use today and they are still as capable of cha</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">lenging modern vehicles as they were then. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Most of these observed sections are situated on the public highway network of u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sealed unclassified roads and byways open to all traffic. There is an extensive cale</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">dar of club events across the country, but despite this high level of activity there is very little evidence of over use of the unsealed roads used for the events.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Classic trials and the rural community</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 18pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">With such a long and continuous history, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">organising</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> clubs have forged close links with the rural communities along the routes of their events. As a result many cou</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">try dwellers see classic trials as part of their local heritage, something to be che</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ished rather than feared, and they look forward to the annual visit of the ‘old cars </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and bikes’ with the same enthusiasm as their parents and grandparents. Every year competitors in classic trials contribute substantial sums to village fund-raising in the areas through which the events pass.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Classic trials and the effect of NERCA 2006</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Motorsport events are regulated and controlled by the Motor Sports Association (MSA) for car events (and road route </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">authorisation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> for all events), and the Amateur Motor Cycle Association (AMCA) and Auto-Cycle Union (ACU) for motorcycle events. These </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> have strict requirements for public relations, before, during, and after the event. These requirements are even more stringent for u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sealed roads and tracks than they are for the normal public road network and exte</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sive local consultation is always necessary before any unsealed public highway is used for a classic trial.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">To understand the effect of NERCA 2006 on the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> of classic trials it is necessary to understand the different </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">authorisation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> processes applicable to u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sealed highways with </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">motorised</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> vehicular rights (unsealed unclassified roads and byways open to all traffic), and those without (restricted byways, bridleways, and footpaths).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In general, for unsealed unclassified roads and byways open to all traffic, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">organisers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> are required to carry out a comprehensive public relations process in accordance with MSA, AMCA and ACU regulations and, if no objections are raised, the event is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">authorised</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. For restricted byways, bridleways, and footpaths, section 33(1) of the Road Traffic Act 1988 requires the written consent of the landowner and occupier, and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">authorisation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> by the local highway authority, before route </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">authorisation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> is gran</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ed by the MSA. This is, quite rightly, a significantly more onerous process than the public relations exercise required for unsealed unclassified roads and byways open to all traffic.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Significant problems have arisen since restricted byways were introduced under the Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000 (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">CRoWA</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> 2000) and these problems have increased under NERCA 2006. The key problem has been one of establishing ow</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ership. Landowners and occupiers had generally assumed that these highways were publicly owned, but local authorities have proved reluctant to accept that they have become the effective landowner for the purpose of giving the consent required u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">der section 33(1). The administrative burden of complying with section 33(1) for r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">stricted byways has resulted in a number of historic observed sections being lost to the events that had used them without any problems for many years.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 20pt; padding-left:16pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The number of unsealed unclassified roads and byways open to all traffic currently used by classic trials is far greater than the number of restricted byways. Far from decreasing bureaucracy at a local level, a wholesale ‘downgrading’ of unsealed uncla</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sified roads and byways open to all traffic to restricted byways will significantly i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">crease the bureaucracy required for local authority </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">authorisation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> of classic reli</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">bility trials, and increase the time and effort required by the volunteers who run these events to such an extent that many will find it impossible to continue. This single change could spell the end of a sporting discipline with a 100+ year history that is still enjoyed today by thousands, either as competitor or spectator.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:130%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>